Gwinnett rejected 595 absentee ballots, a third of all those tossed in Georgia, often without notifying the spurned voters.
Jurisdictions like the states of Washington and Utah took several years to make a smooth transition from polling places to voting by mail.
It progressed as states began to allow people who were seriously ill or away from their homes on Election Day to mail ballots.
Rodriguez said requests for absentee ballots have already skyrocketed, with more than 15,000 applications awaiting approval.
In some states, voters have several days to contact the elections office to solve the problem.